[Beta distributions]\label{exam:beta} 
	For $X \sim \operatorname{Beta}(\alpha, \beta)$, 
	\begin{align}
		m_n & =\prod_{r = 0}^{n-1} \frac{\alpha +r}{\alpha + \beta +r}  = \frac{\Gamma(\alpha + n ) }{\Gamma(\alpha ) } \frac{\Gamma(\alpha + \beta ) }{\Gamma(\alpha + \beta +n  ) }. 
	\end{align} 
	By Stirling's formula, as $n \to \infty$,  
	\begin{align}
		m_n & \sim e^\beta\frac{\Gamma(\alpha + \beta ) }{\Gamma(\alpha ) }\sqrt{\frac{\alpha + n-1}{\alpha + \beta + n-1}} \frac{(\alpha + n-1)^{\alpha + n-1}  }{  (\alpha + \beta + n-1)^{\alpha + \beta + n-1}}, \\
		& \sim e^\beta \frac{\Gamma(\alpha + \beta  ) }{\Gamma(\alpha ) } \frac{(\alpha + n-1)^{\alpha + n-1}}{(\alpha + \beta + n-1)^{\alpha + \beta + n-1}}, \\
		& \sim   n^{-\beta}, \quad \text{as } \left(1+\frac{\beta}{x}\right)^{x} \to e^\beta, \, x\to \infty. 
	\end{align}
	Thus, $m_n = \Theta(n^{-\beta})$.

